Phase A — Secure the secrets first (do this before anything else)

Regenerate/rotate the Azure OpenAI key in the Azure portal — the old one was shared in plain text, so treat it as compromised.
Create a .env file in your project root with:

   AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY=your-new-key
   AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT=https://testingsl1.openai.azure.com/openai/deployments/gpt-4.1
   AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT=gpt-4.1
   USE_SCREENSHOTS=true

Confirm .env is in .gitignore so it never gets committed.

Phase B — Apply the screenshot fix

Replace your aiHealing.ts with the corrected version I gave you.
In the Azure portal, verify your gpt-4.1 deployment is genuinely vision-capable (check the model's supported modalities). This is the single most important check — if it isn't, images are silently ignored and your whole experiment is invalid. If it's text-only, deploy a vision model (gpt-4o or gpt-4.1 vision) and point AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT at it.
Confirm your capture is storing screenshots as JPEG (it is, per your captureElementScreenshot), so the default mime in the fix is correct.

Phase C — Bank a clean baseline

Make sure USE_SCREENSHOTS=true and run capture mode once so the DB holds fresh, good rows with screenshots and DOM:

   MODE=capture npx playwright test novacart-checkout.spec.ts

Spot-check one row in the DB — confirm element_screenshot, full_page_screenshot, context_dom, and smart_locators are all populated.

Phase D — Quick sanity check that vision now works at all
Before the full experiment, prove the plumbing end-to-end on one element.

Break one element's locators in the DB (primary + all smart locators → non-existent selectors), as we did before.
Run heal mode:

    MODE=heal npx playwright test novacart-checkout.spec.ts

In the logs, confirm you see [AI] screenshots ENABLED — 3 image(s) attached and that the element healed via AI. This proves images are being sent. (It still doesn't prove they're being used — that's what Phase E measures.)

Phase E — The actual experiment
The goal is to compare healing with vs without screenshots, on cases where vision could plausibly matter.

Pick your test cases deliberately. Vision can only help when an element moved or restyled but stayed unique. So bias toward those: change an element's id and class and text but keep it the single such element on the page. Avoid the ambiguous-identical-siblings case (it can't heal either way). Aim for maybe 6–10 broken elements across a couple of break-types.
Re-capture a clean baseline (Phase C) so every run starts from the same stored state.
Run 1 — with screenshots. Set USE_SCREENSHOTS=true, break your chosen elements, run heal mode, and record for each element: did it heal, which strategy, the AI confidence, and — critically — was the healed locator correct (did it find the right element, not just a unique one).
Re-capture the baseline again (so Run 2 starts identical), break the same elements the same way.
Run 2 — without screenshots. Set USE_SCREENSHOTS=false, run heal mode, record the same fields.
Optionally Run 3 — screenshots-only (strip the DOM from the prompt) if you want to isolate vision's standalone contribution — this is Dhanush's "change the whole DOM, does it still heal" stress test.

Phase F — Read the results

Compare the two runs on two metrics that matter:

Heal rate — how many recovered.
Correctness — of those that healed, how many found the right element. (This is the one most people skip and it's the most important.)


Interpret honestly:

Similar results in both arms → screenshots are cost without benefit for your app; drop them, save tokens.
With-screenshots recovers cases text-only misses → vision earns its place; keep it for that class.
Don't be surprised by "similar" — a clean parseable DOM usually lets the text path win alone. That's a valid finding, not a failure.



Phase G — Record it

Capture token usage / latency per run too (the API response includes usage) — that's the cost side of the cost/benefit call.
Write the verdict into your research document's section 8.5 / recommendation #9, replacing "to investigate" with your measured conclusion.


A couple of guardrails as you go. Re-capturing a fresh baseline before each run (steps 13, 15) is the easy thing to forget, and skipping it means the two runs aren't comparable — make it a habit. And keep every other variable fixed between Run 1 and Run 2: same elements, same break method, same temperature, only the USE_SCREENSHOTS flag changes. If you change two things at once, the result tells you nothing.
